arts, but haven't heard seen updates in quite a while. Muggle, Pullem, Lena even longer.  Poets, thank you for you contributions and pacem for the script.  And Runiko and other artists, whether polished or satirical keep it coming.  And music, I know Thallas is in his studios pumping out the pieces, but would love to hear more of your works.  And thank you anyone I have missed, it's late...=p<br>
<br>
PLEASE continue.....the existance of the AE forum is not just based on my work alone, even tho a majority of the posts are mine.  That's because I have a big mouth and never STFU.  There is so much talent, just shown on these three pages.  And there is so many creative things out there unheard, unseen, unread that need this forum to come to life, if only for us.<br>
<br>
Do not lose heart if you see no responses, or a low view count.  These things we post are now here, they are permanent, not just ideas swimming in our heads.  If not now, one day when someone is bored at work, they'll click, and your work will be discovered.  And not everyone is verbose with their praise.  Breathe is currently on the Graffe board, and started very very slow.  The view count crawled, the feedback was nonexistant.  But I continued to post religiously, and suddenly, I gained an extra twenty regular readers.  They still for the most part have not said a word, just read regularly, and that is more than good enough for me.  Part of my enjoyment is the creation itself.  That it is enjoyed is icing.  If even ONE person reads my work, then that work is reaching someone, and I am happy.<br>
<br>
A story:<br>
<br>
When I was in semi traction from a car accident, I ended up, after an extended stay in a hotel living in the basement of a movie producer in California.  He was the most miserable prick I have ever met, the embodiment of Hollywood ass.  He was also a writer of scripts and worked on the production end (not the main producer) of films like New Jack City and Posse.  So, his knowledge of the business was there, and he knew screenwriters.  Well, there I was, on Advil because I couldn't deal with heavy painkillers fogging my head, blithely going on about this script I wanted to write, day in and day out.  Finally, he gave me a bit of advice, not to help me, but to shut me up, I think.  But I took the advice to heart, not from respect for the source, but from respect for the basic truth it embodies.<br>
<br>
He said:<br>
<br>
&quot;Writers write.  Talkers talk.&quot;<br>
<br>
I immediately started work on my script 'Knocking on Heaven's Door'.<br>
<br>
Whether you want to become a professional writer, or just like to do it, always remember that...Writers write.  And artists create. <br>
<br>
